In regards to your earlier post to which Class Lass also mentioned SOME QUESTIONS ETC. Fri Jan 2 <br><br>
”As for communism. Yes there was a part of the movement that was communists. Communism has a tradition in the US that is a valid ideology, whether we like it or not. Again judge what people do, not what they think. Like most people communists did good things and bad things. They are people and not monsters, and yes they did believe that the war was wrong.”<br><br>
Jed, evidently you don’t remember how the communist party was involved in the Anti-war movement. The bombings of public buildings, riots and destruction we faced from within. To them the anti-war movement was secondary, to destroy the U.S. from within was their goal.<br>
The anti-America slogans of those days, banners and propaganda are still clearly visible in the news clips of that era. Marxist influence was not apparent to most in part because it was deliberately concealed but it used the movement to put maximum pressure on the U.S. to get out of Vietnam. That would help the Vietnamese revolution and bring victory to the Vietnamese Communists (VC), but you say they are not monsters? Examine their history.<br><br>
I’m reminded of a fish swimming in a nice little rive. He spots a nice morsel of meat dangling from a little string. The fish swims up close and examines it more closely. It’s only a wiggly little worm that would be tasty, full of protein and it would be good for the fish to eat. It would bring him strength and energy and more then likely it’ll taste good. So the fish gets a little close and hits it with his back fins and the little worms goes crazy, wiggling and attracting more attention. The increased activity is far too tempting for that little fish so he opens his mouth and takes a bite swallowing the little worm. But behind the worm he didn’t see the hook. The hook of communism that would soon realm him into dry land and out of the comforts of the world he once knew. It would separate him from his friends and relatives and he would soon die or find himself in captivity only to be eaten later on. When Hayden first went to Hanoi in December of 1965, he fell hook, line, and sinker for everything the Communist told him. The North Vietnamese people did the same thing. They believed Ho Chi Minh after all he was one of their own. The NVA moved south and told the villagers in the South the same thing and some of them believed it, joined the VC but they soon found it wasn’t so. When the Liberation Front won the war, there came no liberty. No freedom, no life, no joy. There was no rejoicing in Saigon by the South Vietnamese population, only grief and despair but I guess you are right Communism is not a monster. They are not a monster in Vietnam or China today and when they dangle little worms (contributions) before President Clinton and Al Gore why, we might as well let them take a bite there’s nothing to fear. <br>

